  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Iron deficiency (ID) affects up to 25% of Swedish infants and severe ID is associated with
      cognitive and behavioral problems. To avoid this, iron supplements or iron-fortified infant
      foods are recommended for infants. However, the optimal iron dose and mode of delivery have
      not yet been established. This is a concern as excessive iron intake may impair growth and
      increase morbidity in iron-sufficient infants. Previous studies have suggested that
      iron-fortified foods may have different effects than iron supplements. In this study, the
      investigators will investigate whether the mode of iron administration (supplementation vs.
      fortification) and the amount consumed (high intakes vs. low intakes) affect iron absorption,
      iron utilization, and zinc absorption in healthy term non-iron-deficient 6-month-old infants.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
